<a name="Byrne & Whiten"></a><b>Byrne, Richard W. and Andrew Whiten. Computation 
and mindreading in primate tactical deception</b>. <a href="#top">Whiten (1991)</a>, 
pp. 127-141. 
<center>
  &nbsp;
</center>
Abstract: (from the chapter) in our initial survey of tactical deception in primates 
(Whiten and Byrne, 1988a), we emphasized the implications for primate psychology 
of obtaining good evidence which implied an understanding of others' intentions 
(and those of deception) by the animal; we then attempted to say what would convince 
us to accept an explanation, and evaluated--usually in the negative--the evidence 
available at the time; we now have a much greater corpus of data available against 
which to test the preliminary conculsions made at that time, and to do so is the 
purpose of this chapter. 
<center>
  &nbsp;
</center>
