<a name="Cheney & Seyfarth"></a><b>Cheney, Dorothy L. and Robert M. Seyfarth. 
Reading minds or reading behaviour? Tests for a theory of mind in monkeys</b>. 
<a href="#top">Whiten (1991)</a>, pp. 175-194. <br>
&nbsp; <br>
Abstract: (from the chapter) describe two experiments designed to investigate 
the ability of monkeys to attribute mental states to others and to distinguish 
between their own knowledge and the knowledge of others... the first experiment 
examines the issue of informing, and considers whether individuals take into account 
their audiences state of mind when alerting them to the presence of food or danger; 
do signallers recognize ignorance in their audience, and, if so, do they make 
any special effort to alert ignorant individuals more than knowledgable ones... 
the second experiment considers the extent to which a monkey's behaviour is influenced 
by her audience's apparent presence, as opposed to her audiences knowledge; do 
monkeys take into account theory of visual perspective when monitoring one another, 
or do they recognize that another individual's perspective, and hence the knowledge 
derived from it, can differ from their own. 
